                    "title": "How UnitedHealth is hampering the Dow on the heels of CEO's resignation",
                    "link": "https://www.axios.com/2025/05/13/unh-stock-unitedhealth-ceo-dow-jones",
                    "description": "<div>Data: <a href=\"https://financialmodelingprep.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Financial Modeling Prep</a>; Chart: Axios Visuals</div><p>The S&amp;P 500 is up 10% over the past month, while the Dow Jones Industrial Average is up only 5%. The main reason why: <a href=\"https://www.axios.com/2025/01/16/unitedhealth-earnings-brian-thompson\" target=\"_blank\">UnitedHealth Group</a>. </p><p><strong>Why it matters: </strong>This time last month, UnitedHealth was the highest-priced stock in the Dow, singlehandedly accounting for 9.2% of the index. The fall in the share price since then represents a drop of 1,938 Dow points, making it that much harder for the average as a whole to show solid gains.</p><hr><p><strong>Driving the news: </strong>UnitedHealth fell another 18% on Tuesday when its CEO <a href=\"https://www.axios.com/2025/05/13/unitedhealth-group-ceo-andrew-witty-brian-thompson\" target=\"_blank\">abruptly resigned</a>, citing \"personal reasons.\" That means it's now down 48% in one month.</p><p><strong>Between the lines:</strong> The Dow is always a bit lopsided. </p><ul><li>While UnitedHealth is now a more typical 4.5% of the average, Goldman Sachs has taken its place in the club of members trading at more than $600 per share. </li><li>As a result, the investment bank, which is worth $185 billion, now comprises 8.7% of the Dow. </li><li>By contrast, <a href=\"https://www.axios.com/2024/11/04/nvidia-stock-dow-jones-intel-ai\" target=\"_blank\">Nvidia</a>, worth $3.19 trillion — that's 17 Goldmans — makes up just 1.9% of the average. </li></ul><p><strong>The bottom line: </strong>There's a good reason why very few people actually invest in the Dow.</p><p><em>Editor's note: This report was updated with stock price changes after Tuesday's close of trading.</em></p>",
                    "content:encoded": "<div>Data: <a href=\"https://financialmodelingprep.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Financial Modeling Prep</a>; Chart: Axios Visuals</div><p>The S&amp;P 500 is up 10% over the past month, while the Dow Jones Industrial Average is up only 5%. The main reason why: <a href=\"https://www.axios.com/2025/01/16/unitedhealth-earnings-brian-thompson\" target=\"_blank\">UnitedHealth Group</a>. </p><p><strong>Why it matters: </strong>This time last month, UnitedHealth was the highest-priced stock in the Dow, singlehandedly accounting for 9.2% of the index. The fall in the share price since then represents a drop of 1,938 Dow points, making it that much harder for the average as a whole to show solid gains.</p><hr><p><strong>Driving the news: </strong>UnitedHealth fell another 18% on Tuesday when its CEO <a href=\"https://www.axios.com/2025/05/13/unitedhealth-group-ceo-andrew-witty-brian-thompson\" target=\"_blank\">abruptly resigned</a>, citing \"personal reasons.\" That means it's now down 48% in one month.</p><p><strong>Between the lines:</strong> The Dow is always a bit lopsided. </p><ul><li>While UnitedHealth is now a more typical 4.5% of the average, Goldman Sachs has taken its place in the club of members trading at more than $600 per share. </li><li>As a result, the investment bank, which is worth $185 billion, now comprises 8.7% of the Dow. </li><li>By contrast, <a href=\"https://www.axios.com/2024/11/04/nvidia-stock-dow-jones-intel-ai\" target=\"_blank\">Nvidia</a>, worth $3.19 trillion — that's 17 Goldmans — makes up just 1.9% of the average. </li></ul><p><strong>The bottom line: </strong>There's a good reason why very few people actually invest in the Dow.</p><p><em>Editor's note: This report was updated with stock price changes after Tuesday's close of trading.</em></p>",
